03838nam a22005415i 9780226575735DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265757357 a10.7208/97802265757352doi  a(DE-B1597)521369  a(OCoLC)1053888213  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB3999.I3bG36 2019 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a199.4922231 aGarver, Eugene, eauthor.10aSpinoza and the Cunning of Imagination /cEugene Garver. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tFirst Part -- tChapter 1. Adequate Ideas Are Infinite Modes -- tChapter 2. Our Knowledge of God and Its Place in Ethics -- tChapter 3. Spinoza's Will to Power: How Does the Conatus Become a Desire to Increase Power? -- tSecond Part -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 5. Conflicts among Emotions, among Ideas, and among People -- tChapter 6. Hilarity and the Goods of Mind and Body -- tChapter 7. The Strength of the Emotions and the Power of the Intellect -- tChapter 8. Ethics and the Ethics: How Does Reason Become Practical? -- tNotes -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Passages in Spinoza's Works0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpinoza's Ethics, and its project of proving ethical truths through the geometric method, have attracted and challenged readers for more than three hundred years. In Spinoza and the Cunning of Imagination, Eugene Garver uses the imagination as a guiding thread to this work. Other readers have looked at the imagination to account for Spinoza's understanding of politics and religion, but this is the first inquiry to see it as central to the Ethics as a whole-imagination as a quality to be cultivated, and not simply overcome. ​Spinoza initially presents imagination as an inadequate and confused way of thinking, always inferior to ideas that adequately represent things as they are. It would seem to follow that one ought to purge the mind of imaginative ideas and replace them with rational ideas as soon as possible, but as Garver shows, the Ethics don't allow for this ultimate ethical act until one has cultivated a powerful imagination. This is, for Garver, "the cunning of imagination." The simple plot of progress becomes, because of the imagination, a complex journey full of reversals and discoveries. For Garver, the "cunning" of the imagination resides in our ability to use imagination to rise above it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aImagination (Philosophy) 4aGod. 4afreedom. 4ageometric method. 4ahuman nature. 4aimagination. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226575735423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226575735.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles